ce:section.ce:para:
In this study, given the unique affinity of the sulfhydryl functional group of thiols for specific metal ions, Ag+ is selected as the fluorescence modulator (Fig. S15a). Ag+ can chelate with N and O containing functional groups on the surface of H-CDs. The fluorescence of H-CDs is changed by promoting non-radiative electron/hole complex annihilation through an effective electron transfer process (Wu et al., 2017). Using the Stern-Volmer equation, the quenching constants (K

                           SV
                        ) for H-CDs with Ag⁺ at different temperatures were determined to be 1.57 × 10⁴, 1.36 × 10⁴, and 1.22 × 10⁴, respectively (Fig. S16a and Table S3). These results demonstrate that quenching efficiency decreases progressively with increasing temperature. Additionally, the minimum quenching rate constant (K

                           q
                        ) across the three temperatures is approximately 4.85 × 1013 L mol−1·s−1 (Fig. S16b), which is significantly higher than the maximum diffusion-controlled quenching constant (2 × 1010 L mol−1·s−1). Furthermore, fluorescence lifetime measurements show that the fluorescence lifetime of H-CDs remains nearly unchanged before and after the addition of Ag⁺ (Fig. S16c). This consistency in fluorescence lifetime further confirms that the fluorescence quenching induced by Ag⁺ is attributed to a static quenching mechanism. The sensing system is constructed based on the interaction among the H-CDs, Ag+, and thiols in this study. To improve the sensitivity of the sensing system, the H-CDs, and Ag+ are integrated into the mPH-NPs. The sensing process occurs within the mPH-NPs, where restricted space and ionic environment inside the micellar core shorten the interaction distance among the H-CDs, Ag+, and analyte, thereby enhancing the sensing effect.

After adding different concentrations of Ag+, the fluorescence of mPH-NPs continuously decreases with the increasing Ag+ concentration (Fig. S17). According to the Stern-Volmer equation, the quenching constants (K

                           SV
                        ) of mPH-NPs with Ag+ are 1.04 × 102, 1.22 × 102, 1.30 × 102, and 1.41 × 102, respectively (Fig. S17 and Table S4). Furthermore, fluorescence lifetime measurements reveal a significant reduction in the fluorescence lifetime of mPH-NPs after the addition of Ag⁺ (Fig. S18). This observation indicates that the interaction between mPH-NPs and Ag⁺ is driven by a collision-induced non-radiative relaxation process, characteristic of dynamic quenching (Brombosz et al., 2010; Gao et al., 2022). The transition from static quenching (single H-CDs) to dynamic quenching in mPH-NPs can be attributed to the unique microenvironment created by micelle assembly. In solution, For H-CDs, static quenching occurs due to the direct interaction between Ag⁺ and the surface functional groups of H-CDs. This interaction leads to the formation of a non-fluorescent complex, signature products of static quenching. In contrast, dynamic quenching typically involves transient collisions between excited-state fluorophores and quenchers. This process relies heavily on molecular diffusion to facilitate the energy transfer responsible for quenching. When H-CDs are assembled into micelles with diblock copolymers, the micelle-induced microenvironment alters the interaction model between H-CDs and Ag⁺. Ag+ enter the micelle shell from the solution environment and then diffuse into the micelle core. Within the core, Ag+ interacts progressively and in a gradient-like manner with H-CDs. This diffusion-driven interaction allows Ag⁺ to sequentially engage with H-CDs from the outer regions of the core, eventually reaching and interacting with H-CDs located in the deeper regions of the core. This sequential interaction establishes a barrier effect within the micelle structure, allowing Ag⁺ to interact with the H-CDs in the micelle core through collision-based interactions. The energy transfer from these transient collisions ultimately leads to dynamic quenching. To achieve effective sensitivity and sensing performance, this study chose a 10 μM Ag+ concentration to construct the mPH-NPs@Ag+ sensing system, based on the evaluation of the linear response concentration range of mPH-NPs to Ag+. The interaction between mPH-NPs and Ag⁺ fundamentally originates from the interaction between H-CDs in the micelle core and Ag⁺, ultimately resulting in the observable fluorescence changes in the micellar system. The response of mPH-NPs to different metal ions is similar to that of single H-CDs, indicating that the response of the mPH-NPs to metal ions is closely linked to the intrinsic response of the H-CDs (Fig. S15b). Upon the addition of thiol analytes, the fluorescence intensity partially recovers to varying degrees due to the competitive binding of the analytes with Ag⁺ in the core of mPH-NPs. Similar to the diffusion mechanism of Ag⁺, upon the addition of thiol, thiol molecules also diffuse into the micelle core and form thiol-Ag⁺ complexes. This interaction is also a dynamic process, therefore suppressing the dynamic quenching ability of Ag+.
